mmunity development: sharing learning to challenge inequality -- tCommunity development and class in the context of an East Asian productivist welfare regime -- tCommunity organising for social change: the scope for class politics -- tCommunity unionism: looking backwards, looking forwards -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book, the second title in the Rethinking Community Development series, starts from concern about increasing inequality worldwide and the re-emergence of community development in public policy debates. It argues for the centrality of class analysis and its associated divisions of power to any discussion of the potential benefits of community development. It proposes that, without such an analysis, community development can simply mask the underlying causes of structural inequality. It may even exacerbate divisions between groups competing for dwindling public resources in the context of neoliberal globalisation. Reflecting on their own contexts, a wide range of contributors from across the global north and south explore how an understanding of social class can offer ways forward in the face of increasing social polarisation. The book considers class as a dynamic and contested concept and examines its application in policies and practices past and present. These include local/global and rural/urban alliances, community organising, ecology, gender and education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAdhikari, Anindita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanks, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarca, Stefania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilon, Anna, econtributor.